You said "subtract". Your shell didn't recognize it as a command.

bash called command_not_found_handle -- a hook that has existed since 2009.
The handler checked five tiers to figure out what you meant:

  T0  lookup table     exact match against ~/.subtract/lookup.tsv    <5ms
  T1  embedding        semantic similarity against man page corpus   <200ms
  T2  local model      7B parameter model reads the man page         1-5s
  T4  cloud            remote model, only if configured              1-30s
  --  honest failure   "not found" -- no fabrication                 0ms

T0 matched "subtract" in the lookup table. This message is the result.

That's the entire product. Natural language at a bash prompt, resolved
through the tiers above. The handler is six lines. The knowledge base
is the man pages that already ship with your system.

This runs beside your OS, not instead of it. Windows (WSL), macOS
(Terminal.app), or any Linux. Your existing tools stay. subtract is
the layer underneath -- and it fades as you learn the commands yourself.

https://subtract.ing
https://github.com/03-git/subtract
